list.item:
talio esto
11th EB, ‘Roman Law’ 538: The original purpose [of a peace-offering to the kinsmen of a thief caught and killed in the act] must have been to stay the blood revenge, but in the Tables it can only have been intended to stay the prosecution which it was incumbent on the kinsmen of a murdered man to institute. So with talionic penalties: “si membrum rupit ni cum eo pacit, talio esto”—such, according to Gellius, were the words of the laws of the Tables, and they undoubtedly recognize talion, “an eye for an eye, a tooth for a tooth”;
VI.C.3.138(d)
